# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crossplane
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] The **29th International 500-Mile Sweepstakes Race** was held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Friday, May 30, 1941.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] The start of the race was delayed due to a fire that swept through the garage area on race morning.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] No persons were injured, but one car in the field was destroyed.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] The race rolled off with only 31 cars, and ran to its scheduled distance.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] This would be the final "500" prior to the United States involvement in World War II along with the final race under with Eddie Rickenbacker as president of the speedway.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] He kept the track locked during the war before selling the track in November 1945 to Tony Hulman.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] The 1941 race was the second, and most recent "500" to be recorded with co-winners.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Floyd Davis started the race in the #16 Noc-Out Hose Clamp Special.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] His teammate Mauri Rose started the race on the pole position in the #3 car, but his dropped out early with spark plug trouble.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Rose took over behind the wheel of the #16 car on lap 73, and drove that car to victory.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Davis and Rose were credited as co-winners, and it was the first of three "500" victories for Rose.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Sam Hanks was injured in a practice crash the day before the race and withdrew.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Rather than elevate the first alternate to the starting field, Hanks was credited with 33rd place.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] On the morning of the race a fire broke out in the "Gasoline Alley" garage area.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] George Barringer's revolutionary rear-engined car was destroyed.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] At the time, the car was being refueled (with gasoline).
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] In a nearby garage, another car which was owned by Joel Thorne was being worked on with a welder.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] The fumes caught fire from the sparks of the welding, and a huge fire broke out which burned down about a third of the southern bank of garages.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] The start of the race was delayed by a couple hours, and fire fighters had trouble getting to the Speedway to put out the blaze due to the heavy race day traffic.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Barringer's car was withdrawn, and he was credited with 32nd finishing position.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] With both Sam Hanks and Barringer out, the race lined up with only 31 cars.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Various equipment, tools, parts, and other supplies were lost in the fire.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Two cars that did not qualify for the race were reported to have been damaged.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] However, all of the other cars that qualified for the race were safely evacuated.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] The fire was put out, but the site smoldered throughout the day, and smoke continued to rise even after the race had safely started.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] About a month later, the entire garage complex was demolished.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] At some point during summer and fall of 1941, a new Gasoline Alley garage area was built in its place.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] However, due to the war, the new garages would sit unused until 1946.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Two-time defending champion (and three-time winner overall) Wilbur Shaw crashed while leading on lap 152, and failed in his bid to become the first driver to three-peat at the Indianapolis 500 (and first four-time winner).
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] As of 2025, no driver has ever won the Indianapolis 500 three consecutive years.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Going down the mainstretch, the car lost control, and hit the outside wall, rupturing the gas tank.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Shaw was drenched with fuel, and suffered a back injury which left him immobile for several minutes.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Despite the fuel spill, the fuel did not ignite, and Shaw was brought to safety by the medical staff.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] It is believed that the morning garage fire had an effect on Shaw's efforts.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] At some point before the race, Shaw's crew was preparing his tires for race day, and used chalk to write notes on the spare tires.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] One particular wheel was determined to be out of balance, and rather than being discarded, it was labeled in chalk with the words "USE LAST".
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] However, the firefighters' water hoses are believed to have washed off the chalk message.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Shaw inadvertently took on the bad wheel during a pit stop, which caused his crash.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Shaw never drove another competitive lap at the Speedway.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] He did participate in a special private tire test at the Speedway during World War II and became president of the track in 1946.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Floyd Davis was the starting driver for the #16 car.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] On lap 72, Davis came in for a pit stop, and was relieved by Mauri Rose.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Rose had started the race in another car and dropped out earlier.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Car owner Lou Moore was apparently unsatisfied with Davis' performance thus far in the race, and ordered Rose to take over.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Rose charged up the standings and took the lead in the #16 car, and went on to win.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Both drivers were credited as "co-winners," similar to what occurred in the 1924 race.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] This marked the last time that one car would carry two drivers to victory at Indy.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] Speedway president Eddie Rickenbacker did not attend the race, and instead listened to it on the radio.
[src:crossplane/1941-indianapolis-500] He was recovering from injuries suffered in a near-fatal plane crash a few months before the race.
[src:crossplane/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:crossplane/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:crossplane/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:crossplane/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:crossplane/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:crossplane/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:crossplane/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:crossplane/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:crossplane/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:crossplane/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:crossplane/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:crossplane/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:crossplane/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:crossplane/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:crossplane/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:crossplane/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The **BRM P261**, also known as the **BRM P61 Mark II**, is a Formula One motor racing car, designed and built by the British Racing Motors team in Bourne, Lincolnshire, England.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The BRM P261 was introduced for the 1964 Formula One season, and its design was an evolution of Tony Rudd's one-off BRM P61 car of 1963.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The P261 had a relatively long racing career; variants of the car were still being entered for Formula One World Championship Grands Prix as late as 1968.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] During the course of their front-line career, BRM P261s won six World Championship races, in the hands of works drivers Graham Hill and Jackie Stewart, and finished second in both the Drivers' and Constructors' Championship standings in 1964 and 1965.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Stewart, Hill and Richard Attwood also used works P261s to compete in the Tasman Series in 1966.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The BRMs dominated, with Stewart winning four, Hill two, and Attwood one of the 1966 Tasman Series' eight races.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The works-backed Reg Parnell Racing team returned in 1967 with Stewart and Attwood, where Stewart added another two wins to his tally.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] In terms of races won and total championship points scored, the P261 was the most successful car in BRM's history.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Colin Chapman's monocoque Lotus 25 of 1962 had put the writing on the wall for older spaceframe chassis designs, and most other Formula One constructors hurriedly started work on their own monocoque cars.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The BRM P261 was British Racing Motors's first fully monocoque chassis.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Its prototype, the one-off P61 introduced in 1963, pioneered many of BRM's monocoque elements, but used a tubular subframe for its rear engine mounting.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] As its name suggests, with the P261 (or P61 Mark II) designer Tony Rudd simply built upon the P61's structure, rather than introducing a completely new car.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] To emphasize this continuity, the P261 chassis numeration continues the P61 sequence, with the first P261 chassis being numbered 2612.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] BRM had some previous experience of stressed skin construction with the BRM P25, so Rudd was in a good position to be able to exploit the new technology to the full.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] This previous experience meant that Rudd's use of the monocoque was somewhat different from the pioneering Lotus's frame.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Where the 25 had been a channel-section frame with an open top, within which the driver sat, the P261 chassis was a slim tubular-section, into which a hole was cut to allow the driver to gain access.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] To replace the P61's subframe the side pontoons of the P261 chassis were extended behind the driver's seat, and the engine was mounted between them.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Within the pontoons, rubber cells were used to retain fuel.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] This caused complications early in the P261's life, as BRM's new, high-exhaust version of the *P56* V8 engine was not ready for the start of the 1964 season, and holes had to be cut in the pontoons to allow the exhaust pipes of the older, low-exhaust version to pass through them.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The centre exhaust engine appeared at the 1964 Italian Grand Prix in Graham Hill's new chassis "2616" and this and "2617", which was Jackie Stewart's regular car in 1965, were the only two P261s which did not have the exhaust slots.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] These were plated over on the earlier cars which remained in service, but could be opened up if necessary to fit outside exhaust engines, as happened in the 1967 Tasman Championship.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] In comparison to the older engine, the position of the inlet trumpets and exhaust manifolds had been switched, so that the exhausts exited on the upper surface of the engine, within the cylinder vee, and the inlets protruded above the chassis pontoons on either side of the car.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Between the chassis pontoons the engine was covered with a removable, curved panel.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Completing the engine cowling was a near-circular gearbox and differential cover at the rear, through which the tail pipes of the exhausts protruded.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Shifting the inlets to the outer edges of the car allowed the engine to ingest cooler, denser air, boosting the motor's power output.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The compact exhaust bundle also allowed a svelte packaging of the engine bay.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] However, the heat build-up from the confined manifold necessitated cutting a hole in the top of the engine cover.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Despite this, the BRM P261's barrel-shaped rear end became one of its most distinctive visual characteristics.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The engine's internals remained almost unaltered from the Peter Berthon-designed unit which was installed in the V8 version of the P57, the BRM P578, with which Graham Hill had won the World Championship in 1962.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] BRM had experimented with a four-valve-per-cylinder version of the engine, but this was abandoned in favour of the tried and trusted, oversquare (68.5 x 50.8 mm), fuel-injected, two-valve, quad-cam configuration.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The 1965 Formula One engine was rated at 210 bhp (157 kW) at 11,000 rpm, but was upgraded at Monza to 220 bhp (164 kW) at 11,750 rpm.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] In its Formula One form the engine had a capacity of 1,498 cc (91 cu in), but for the early 1966 Tasman Series races this was increased to 1,916 cc (116.9 cu in).
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] In 1966 the Formula One upper engine size limit was raised from 1.5 to 3.0 litres, and the 1.9-litre Tasman unit was pressed into service for the World Championship as well.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] It was further uprated to 2.0 litres as the season progressed.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] For the P261's 1967 trip to the Antipodes the engine capacity was stretched yet further, providing the ultimate 2,136 cc (130.3 cu in) version, which also saw service in a few Formula One races later in the year.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] In an attempt to keep the P261 competitive into 1968, the fifth chassis was fitted with the new, 3-litre V12 BRM engine, but without success.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Fully independent double wishbone suspension was employed at all four corners.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Another significant change made from the P61 design was to move the suspension shock absorber components outboard at the rear.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] This switch was initially made to accommodate the extra cam-cover space needed to employ the 32-valve motor, but though that unit was shelved the suspension geometry was retained.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] At the front, the coil spring and damper units were retained within the monocoque skin, resulting in a clean, aerodynamic profile around the car's nose-cone.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Braking was by outboard-mounted, Dunlop disc brakes all round.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] A total of six BRM P261 cars were constructed, with both the first and last chassis built being written off during their careers and rebuilt by the factory.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The BRM P261 made its race debut at the non-Championship Daily Mirror Trophy race, at Snetterton on 14 March 1964.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Only one car was ready at the time, and it was entered for long-serving works driver Graham Hill.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The car immediately showed its promise, as Hill took second place in qualifying, beaten only by newly crowned World Champion Jim Clark's Lotus 25.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Unfortunately for Hill, in the race itself he retired following an accident on only the seventh lap.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The early season shakedown races continued well for the BRM team; Hill set fastest lap at Goodwood on 30 March, and was only prevented from winning when the car's rotor arm dropped off two laps from the end.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Hill added a further two second-place finishes, at the Aintree 200 and BRDC International Trophy races, before the first race of the World Championship season.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Despite the rather interim nature of its engine and chassis configuration, on its World Championship debut at the 1964 Monaco Grand Prix the BRM P261 had the best of starts.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Although Hill and team-mate Richie Ginther only managed to qualify in third and eighth places, respectively, in the race Hill set fastest lap, and the two P261s finished first and second.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] It was the second of Hill's five victories on the Côte d'Azure.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Hill continued to perform well throughout the first half of the season, and took a string of three back-to-back second places in France, Britain and Germany.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Ironically, it was with the introduction of the proper, high-exhaust version of the engine in Italy that the car's reliability began to falter.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] At Monza Hill qualified on the front row of the grid, but as he sat waiting for the flag to drop his clutch seized open, and his car sat stationary as the rest of the field streamed past him.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Hill bounced back to win in the United States, but finished out of the points at the season finale in Mexico following a collision with Bandini.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] With reasonable results from Ginther, BRM finished the season second in the Constructors' Championship, with Hill also second in the Drivers' Championship.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] BRM's new driver signing for the 1965 Formula One season was promising young Scot Jackie Stewart.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] In his very first race meeting for the team, the 1965 Race of Champions at Brands Hatch, Stewart used his P261 to immediately make his mark, taking second place in the overall aggregate positions after two heats.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Stewart took his first outright race win in that year's International Trophy race.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Fortunately for BRM, the car's late season lack of reliability had been cured by the time that the 1965 World Championship season began, and of the BRM P261's twenty Grand Prix starts only four did not result in a points-scoring finish.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Hill again won in Monaco and the USA, while Stewart eventually took a closely contested Italian Grand Prix, his first ever World Championship race win in only his first Formula One season, wiping out memories of the previous year's humiliation at Monza.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Again BRM took second spot in the constructors' standings at the season's end, with Hill and Stewart taking second and third, respectively, in the Drivers' Championship.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Following the end of the 1965 World Championship season, BRM fitted two of their chassis with the enlarged, 1.9-litre version of the V8 engine, and shipped them to Australia and New Zealand to compete in the Tasman Series.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Hill and Stewart accompanied them, along with substitute driver Richard Attwood, and immediately set about dominating the championship, despite the P261 giving away over half a litre to the older Climax-engined cars.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The lead pair finished first and second at the season's opening race: the New Zealand Grand Prix.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] With Hill sitting out the remainder of the New Zealand rounds, Attwood proved an able replacement and took one win and a second place from his three race starts.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] On Hill's return to the team for the Australian rounds he picked up a second race win, and his results were strong enough for him to finish second in the Championship standing, beaten only by team-mate Stewart who had taken four wins from the series' eight-race schedule.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Back in Europe, only Brabham, Ferrari and Cooper had managed to secure a true 3-litre motor for their Formula One vehicles.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Others, like BRM, were due to start the 1966 Formula One season with enlarged versions of their older engines.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] BRM did have the ambitious H16 engine in development, but for the first few races the team were forced to use the, by now two-year-old, P261.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Despite this hindrance Jackie Stewart took first place at the season opening Monaco Grand Prix.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] However, when Jack Brabham's Brabham BT19 was on song, Hill and Stewart's P261s were outclassed, and were replaced by the H16-engined P83 for the season's final three races.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Team Chamaco Collect entered American Bob Bondurant in five races, and British-born South African Vic Wilson in one.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Wilson was the cousin of team boss Bernard White, who subsequently renamed his team to the less-exotic Bernard White Racing and entered a privateer P261 for Innes Ireland in the final two races of 1966, but he failed to finish on either occasion.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Rather than sending the full works team down under for the 1967 Tasman Series season, BRM chose to lend their support to the private Reg Parnell Racing team.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] The Parnell team prepared two P261s, for works driver Stewart and previous year's race winner Richard Attwood.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] With the 2.1-litre V8 engine fitted, Stewart again made certain of a BRM victory in the season opening New Zealand GP.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Despite scoring four straight podium finishes, Attwood was replaced by Piers Courage and Chris Irwin for the Australian rounds.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Although Courage failed to make a mark, Irwin finished the season by taking third place in Longford.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Stewart finished equal second in the series standings, but with fewer than half the points of Championship-winner Jim Clark.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Parnell continued to run a 2.1-litre P261 for Chris Irwin and Piers Courage during the subsequent 1967 Formula One season, and Bernard White ran another for David Hobbs at the British and Canadian Grands Prix.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] However, with the P83 now the main works car, the Bourne works team only fielded a P261 twice in the World Championship, although Stewart did manage third place at the 1967 French Grand Prix in his.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Pedro Rodríguez took a P261 back to the Tasman Series for one final time in the 1968 season, and he took second place at the Longford round.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] But with the widespread availability of the Cosworth DFV 3-litre V8 in the 1968 Formula One season there was little reason for running with an outclassed and underpowered old chassis in Europe beyond the end of 1967.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Nevertheless, chassis number 2615 was fitted with the new BRM V12 engine, the H16's replacement, for a few non-Championship race entries.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Its best result was third place in the Grand Prix de Madrid, although it was only the second race that the car managed to finish all year.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Australian driver Frank Gardner attempted to qualify the V12 engined car for the 1968 Italian Grand Prix, but his time was too slow.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Ian Mitchell's privateer P261 did appear in the British Formula 5000 Guards Trophy races in 1969, but he failed to finish a single race.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Tony Dean drove a P261 in the 1969 Madrid Grand Prix at Jarama.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Contemporary reports show that he finished second but only completed 39 out of 40 laps.
[src:crossplane/brm-p261] Peter Gethin broke down on lap 40 and some later reports classify him as second.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The **crossplane** or **cross-plane** is a crankshaft design for piston engines with a 90° angle (phase in crank rotation) between the crank throws.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The crossplane crankshaft is the most popular configuration used in V8 road cars.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Aside from the V8 already mentioned, other examples of configurations using such 90° piston phases include straight-2, straight-4, V2, and V4 engines.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Crossplane crankshafts could feasibly be used with a great many other cylinder configurations, but the advantages and disadvantages described below may not apply to any or all of them and must be considered on a case-by-case basis.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The most common crossplane crankshaft for a 90° V8 engine has four crankpins, each serving two cylinders on opposing banks, offset at 90° from the adjacent crankpins.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The first and last of the four crank pins are at 180° with respect to each other as are the second and third, with each pair at 90° to the other, so that viewed from the end the crankshaft forms a cross.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The crankpins are therefore in two planes *crossed* at 90°, hence the name *crossplane*.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] A crossplane V8 crankshaft may have up to nine main bearings in the case of an eight throw design, and usually has five bearings supporting four throws each with a shared crank pin.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The crossplane design was first proposed in 1915, and developed by Cadillac and Peerless, both of whom produced flatplane V8s before introducing the crossplane design.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Cadillac introduced the first crossplane in 1923, with Peerless following in 1924.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The crossplane V8 was developed to produce a smoother engine than possible with a flatplane design.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Because four pistons stop and start together in the same plane in both banks, the second-order forces inherent to the flatplane design stack up and become noticeable in large displacement engines.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Each bank of the crossplane engine has four distinct piston phases that cancel the second-order free forces entirely, leaving only minor vibrations due to variation in masses of components during manufacture.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] However, the 180° disposition of the end and middle crank throws does result in a primary (crank speed) rocking couple, which in the 90° V case can be countered by weighting the crankshaft appropriately, much like a V-Twin.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Other V-angles generally require a balancer shaft to keep things as smooth.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Because of the heavy counterweights on each crank throw, most crossplane V8s have very heavy crankshafts, meaning they are not as free revving in general as their flatplane counterparts.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Early Chrysler Hemi V8 had heavy counterweights, but the middle two positions on both sides of the center main bearing (the third of 5 mains) did not have any counterweight.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Because these positions are located close to the center of engine, they contribute less to countering any rocking motions - hence the use of external balance weights (e.g. in the crank nose pulley), which requires less extra mass for the same balancing effect.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] However, the uneven firing in each bank (see below), as well as the 90° piston phases themselves, do contribute to torsion in the crankshaft which can be noticeable - it is for this reason that crossplane V8s have tuned mass dampers fitted to them, again usually on the free end of the crankshaft.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] In later years, racecar engine builders took notice in the high revving potential of flat plane crank V8s.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The first hi-RPM flat plane crank engine was developed in Novi, Michigan by Bud Winfield, and raced at the 1941 Indianapolis 500 as the Winfield Special.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] This engine, later known as the Novi Engine, was raced at Indy up until 1962.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] In Formula One, in 1962 Coventry Climax adopted the high revving flat plane engine with their Mk.III FWMV in 1963.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] BRM made the same switch at about the same time, and this carried over into their 1964 P261 F1 car.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Four stroke crossplane V8 engines have even 90 degree ignition intervals, but unevenly spaced firing patterns within each cylinder bank.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The firing order on the Left and Right banks are generally LRLLRLRR or RLRRLRLL with each 'L' or 'R' ignition being separated by 90° crank rotation for a total of 720° for eight ignitions.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] As can be seen by counting four characters to the right of each 'L' or 'R' (4 x 90° = 360°), the cylinders that fire (and thus exhaust) at 360° phase difference reside in opposite banks in a crossplane V8.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The actual intervals in each bank are 180-90-180-270 crankshaft degrees, in various orders depending on the engine, and not usually in the same order in each bank.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The exact combinations depends on the crankshaft "handedness", the direction of rotation and which of the 360° pairs is ignited first in the order.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The characteristic "burble" of a crossplane V8 comes from the exhaust manifold design, which typically merges all four exhaust ports on each bank of four cylinders into one exit for convenience.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] This accentuates the pattern outlined above, sometimes described as "potato-potato", mimicking the alternating sequential interval and longer gap.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The specific firing order of the engine and the exhaust configuration can lead to subtle variations which may or may not be noticeable to enthusiasts.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Other sounds are possible by careful grouping of the exhaust pulses, but the packaging (space) requirements generally make this unfeasible in road-going machines.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Even-firing pairs are disposed in opposite banks, so long equal-length exhaust pipes are needed to merge these pairs and achieve uniform scavenging.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] One of the earliest examples of such a tuned exhaust for a crossplane V8 was as fitted to the 1.5 Litre Coventry Climax FWMV Mk.I and Mk.II engines in the early 1960s - these were known to get in the way of servicing the engine itself, however.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Many racing crossplane V8 engines (like Ford 4.2L DOHC V8 for Indy racing) had exhaust ports on the inside of the V angle to make these exhaust pipe lengths shorter and the merges easier to achieve without causing packaging issues.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The Ford GT40 made the concept on production-based V8s famous with an elaborate arrangement of long exhaust pipes nicknamed "Bundle of Snakes".
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Such systems are also sometimes called "180-degree headers", referencing the 180° intervals collected in each branch, similar to a flatplane V8.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Prior to this, straight individual "stack pipes", or "zoomies", were sometimes used (e.g.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] BRM) to avoid the negative impact of uneven exhaust pulse interference on scavenging, at the cost of not benefiting from the positive extraction effects of merging, as above.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Even afterwards on many occasions the performance deficit was accepted and ordinary 4-into-1 systems per bank were employed for convenience.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Some of the gap can be made up with performance-oriented 4-into-2-into-1, or "Tri-Y", exhausts, e.g. those used in NASCAR and V8 supercars.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Unlike in a V8, a crossplane arrangement in inline-four engines results in an unevenly distributed firing pattern, so the use tends to be limited to extremely high-revving engines.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] In such engines, the advantage of less secondary imbalance outweighs the irregular firing interval disadvantage.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] This design, not having pistons disposed at 90° to each other in separate banks, requires a balance shaft to counter the rocking vibration disadvantages arising from plane imbalances on reciprocating mass and rotating mass.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Please see engine balance article for details.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The 2009 Yamaha YZF-R1 motorcycle uses a crossplane crankshaft, employing a crank-speed balance shaft to counter the inherent rocking vibration (primary rocking couple) described above.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] This was inspired by Yamaha's M1 MotoGP racing models, which continue to use crossplane cranks to this date because of their significant inertial torque advantage at the extreme high rpm operation these engines see.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Yamaha claims advances in metal forging technologies made this a practical production sportbike.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The so-called Fath-Kuhn straight-four engine, as used to relative success in motorcycle and side-car racing from 1968 by the private URS racing team, was also a crossplane type.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] It was a different configuration to that normally used in a V8 or indeed in the Yamaha above, with two of the throws being swapped around - i.e. the throws may be described as being at absolute angles of 0, 90, 180, and 270 degrees, versus the more usual 0, 90, 270, 180.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] This results in a slightly reduced primary rocking couple, but introduces higher order couples of much lower magnitude.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The different layout was primarily chosen to reduce the impact of the inertial torsion inherent with crank throws spaced 90° apart due to the pistons being accelerated (start-stop motion), given this engine was meant to be high revving and inertial forces scale as to the square of engine speed.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The reduction in torsion was achieved by splitting the crank into two separate parts, geared together, from their respective midpoints, via a counter-shaft, from which power was delivered to the gearbox.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] It is likely this inertial torsion within the crank is the reason for Yamaha citing crank forging improvements as a reason for the cross-plane crank being viable in a road bike.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] It is less of an issue in the V8 because each throw is shared by two pistons already offset by 90°.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Crossplane crankshafts used in a four-stroke, four-cylinder engine result in uneven firing, since the natural separation of ignition events is (720°/4 =) 180° in such an engine (hence the popularity of 180° flat-plane crank).
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The firing intervals (the space between ignition events) for the crossplane R1 and URS engines are 90-180-270-180 (crank degrees), but other intervals are possible including those due to so-called big-bang firing orders.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The uneven firing is the cause of the distinctive sound of this configuration, which is superficially a combination of the 270-450 (90° V-Twin), 180-540 (180° straight twin) and 90-630 ("twingled" V-Twin) intervals, the dominant interval perceptually being the 270° one.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The 90° throw separation would make the cross-plane crank a natural choice for a two-stroke straight four, providing the advantages of both evenly spaced firing and less secondary vibration when the increased rocking vibrations are countered with a crank-speed balance shaft.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Straight-twin motorcycle engines (a.k.a.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] "parallel-twin" and "vertical twin") historically came in two types, neither of which were "cross plane": 360° cranks with their pistons moving in tandem, or 180° cranks with their pistons moving in opposite phase.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Beginning with Edward Turner's Triumph Speed Twin, most classic English 4-stroke roadsters (Triumph, BSA, Norton, Royal Enfield, etc) used the 360° cranks; but in the 1960s, Honda adopted the 180° cranks for its OHC 4-stroke parallel twins, such as the 450cc "Black Bomber" and CB500T.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] On a small displacement bike, the rocking couple was acceptable without a balance shaft, particularly when compared to a similar sized 360° twin similarly lacking a balance shaft.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The 400cc Dream/Hawk CB250/400T replaced the 4 cylinder CB400F, and to obtain smoother running closer, it had a 360° twin with a balance shaft - the even firing of the 360° crank noticeably smoother than the uneven 180° crank.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] In 1995, Yamaha fitted 270° crankshaft to its TRX850 and in 1996 to the TDM850 MK2, plus a balance shaft to counter the resulting combination of free forces and rocking couples.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The 270° crank has smaller free forces than the 360° crank (but much larger than the 180° crank) and smaller rocking couples than the 180° crank (the 360° crank has no such couple).
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Whilst firing was as uneven as a 90° V-Twin, the 270° crank was not as uneven as the 180°.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] The 270° configuration represents a successful compromise and has been adopted for Honda's NC700 and 2016 Africa Twin, Hinckley Triumph's Scrambler and Thunderbird cruiser, Yamaha's MT-07 / FZ-07 and a number of others.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Some customising engineers have modified British and Yamaha XS 650 parallel-twin motorcycles to become 277° engines, close to cross-plane crankshafts (aka *offset crankshaft* or *rephased crankshaft*) with success in reducing the vibration from stock 360° vertical-twins.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] This is seemingly inspired by the earlier work of Phil Irving.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] On 2-stroke parallel-twin engines, the 180° crank configuration was almost universally adopted, giving two power strokes in each revolution.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Examples include quite large capacity bikes such as the 598cc Scott Squirrel or 498cc Suzuki T500.
[src:crossplane/crossplane] Two exceptions with 360° crankshafts are the Yankee, and the military edition of the Jawa 350.
